Headline: AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK: It's Not Called Smart For Nothing
Story: Edited by Paul Vigna     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES       (call: 201-938-5172; email: paul.vigna@dowjones.com)       AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK can be found using N/DJMT and I/AUT     4:13 (Dow Jones) One of if not the smallest cars here is the Smart car, a DaimlerChrysler (DCX) product that's been popular in Europe and will make its US debut in the 1Q08, being sold through United Auto Group (UAG). The little car - it's being displayed outside Cobo Hall maneuvering through and parking between limos and could almost fit in the bed of a Silverado - is being introduced at the "right time," UAG CEO Roger Penske says. Penske wouldn't make a production estimate, but did say jokingly it would be in the "double digits." Penske was asked how he would reply to potential customers worried about driving such a small car on US roads alongside all those big SUVs. He said the car is small, but it's high-tech and has a plethora of safety features. "It's amazing how resilient it is because of the design." (PJV)   3:52 (Dow Jones) With all the high-tech, space-age know-how on display, it was an usual sight to see a man standing in the lobby of Cobo Hall next to one of the lowest tech vehicles around: a sled. A team of five barking, yelping huskies was attached to the sled, and they ran into the main hall and onto DaimlerChrysler's (DCX) exhibit space, which was covered in a sheet of ice, to kick off DCX's presentation. DCX introduced several new models with its 4matic drive - the general theme being 4matic can handle any terrain - and a few with its Bluetec, clean diesel engines. The dogs were followed by hockey players and ice skaters. "I hope you didn't expect to see me on skates," CEO Dr. Dieter Zetsche said. (PJV)   3:25 (Dow Jones) GM CEO Rick Wagoner says the Chevy Volt electric car "isn't about science projects." The auto maker has set aside hundreds of millions of dollars to get the electric car started, but Wagoner indicates the company will spend significantly more than $500M to make it a reality. Wagoner says the company needs to build more than the 1,000 or so electric cars the company did in its last electric car effort, the abandoned EV1 program, and adds their vision is clearer this time. Instead, GM would ideally like to build "hundreds of thousands, (even) millions a year...this is an opportunity to deliver results." He concedes, however, there are question marks around the technology. "Production time will depend on development of battery technology," he says. (JDS/PI)   2:16 (Dow Jones) GM Vice Chairman Bob Lutz called it an "inconvenient truth" that his company has indeed started development of a new "E-Flex" vehicle, the Chevrolet Volt, which run on electricity as well as biodiesel, ethanol and, yes, gasoline. The Volt has a sporty look, WSJ.com observes, and Lutz noted an electric vehicle can also "look good." The Volt can drive 40 miles before other fuels need to help recharge and Lutz emphasized that 78% of Americans live within 20 miles of work. He said if someone drove to work, ran nearby errands and charged the car every night, the owner would never have to buy gasoline for the lifetime of the vehicle, he said. For now, though, the Volt remains only an intriguing concept. (MS)   (http://blogs.wsj.com/autoshow/)   1:26 (Dow Jones) In the minutes leading up to Chrysler Group's big auto show press conference, there were giant loafs of bread flanking the stage. A kitchen counter was in the middle, as if on a cooking show. Irreverent slices of cartoon bread danced on a giant screen.   What was the theme for this revamped minivan unveiling event - the "best thing since sliced bread" or "something's cooking at Chrysler"? Nope. Instead, it was Chrysler Group's focus on its "bread and butter" vehicles. The DaimlerChrysler AG (DCX) unit rolled out the latest versions of its Dodge Caravan and Chrysler Town & Country minivans, replete with a host of gadgets and options. Not listed: the wood paneling seen on the old Plymouth Voyager minivan, also rolled out as Chrysler touted it's long pioneering position in the vehicle segment.   Chrysler President Tom LaSorda was joined on stage by celebrity chef Bobby Flay, and the two made a couple of quick dishes that represent the Chrysler and Dodge brands - spicy pork loin with mango for Dodge and a smooth chocolate ganache cake for Chrysler.   When LaSorda took a turn icing the cake, Flay told the executive, "I can tell you've spent a lot of time in the hot kitchen," to which LaSorda replied, "The kitchen's been pretty hot lately, I'll tell you," a reference to Chrysler's tough 2006. (JDK, TKS)   1:08 (Dow Jones) Ford's (F) new leader, Alan Mulally, looked like a lifer in his appearance at the company's press conference. Driven out in a glistening new 500 sedan, Mulally was poised and energetic in discussing Ford's cars and prospects, sounding much like a man who's excited about what he's doing. After the event, North American head Mark Fields - who matched Mulally in the enthusiasm department - said he expects the auto maker's sales will be down slightly, with light vehicle sales of roughly 16.4M, as the US economy slows down. Fields expects GDP of 2%-2.5%, with a moderating job market and weak housing market. (PJV)   12:40 (Dow Jones) Was that a press conference or a rock concert? Ford's (F) flashy press conference featured deafening rock music, a light show and five giant video screens. Executives like Bill Ford Jr. and Mark Fields were driven onto the stage in glistening cars and greeted like guitar heroes. The music was so loud it drowned out the engine on Ford's concept muscle car, the Interceptor. Even Bill Gates was trotted out via satellite to talk about Ford and Microsoft's (MSFT) "Sync" project. 2006 was difficult, Bill Ford said, and 2007 will be pivotal, but the company's laid the foundation for a better Ford. (PJV)   11:05 (Dow Jones) Johnson Control (JCI) is trying to beef up the gadget-connection capability in cars, an issue in the spotlight at this year's North American International Auto Show with the Ford/Microsoft deal. JCI on Sunday unveiled its Mobile Device Gateway, which would allow drivers to use Bluetooth, USB and serial ports to plug in cell phones, MP3 players and other devices and use them as if they were factory-installed. JCI is working with automakers on making it available in 2010 and "maybe even a little earlier," says Scott Wright, vice president of electronic sales and marketing. The system expands on JCI's current Bluetooth system. (TAK)   10:53 (Dow Jones) The media are descending on Detroit. The centennial North American auto show kicks off today, with a full slate of events and hoards of journalists jockeying for position. GM is building the early buzz, with its glitzy runway show last night and its fairly surprising sweep of the North American car and truck awards this morning. The company also has a noon press conference where it will unveil its latest concept car, the Chevy Volt, and talk about getting back into the electric car market - just as soon as it develops a new type of battery. (PJV)     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 16:13 ET (21:13 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: Mulally Takes In First Auto Show
Story: (The following items are culled from reporters covering the 2007 North American International Auto Show in Detroit. The show kicked off Sunday with a series of media events.)   * * *   DETROIT (Dow Jones)--Ford Co.(F) CEO Alan Mulally, caught walking the floor of the Detroit Auto Show Sunday morning, said he's waiting to hear if his 87-year-old mother can make it to this year's show. The CEO regularly corresponds with his mother and she has taken to calling him her favorite "car guy" even though Mulally is better schooled in airplanes after a long career at Boeing Co. (BA). Mulally was hired in September and has never been to the Detroit event. When asked what he thinks of his first show, Mulally said he liked what he saw but is most excited for the Ford press conference later in the day. (John Stoll)   * * *   It was hard to tell if it was actual surprise or just corporate enthusiasm, but there was a joyful gasp that escaped from the attendees at the 2007 North American car of the year award when Saturn's Aura took the prize, besting the other finalists, Toyota's (TM) Camry and Honda Motor Corp.'s (HMC) Fit. Jill Lajdziak, general manager of General Motor's (GM) Saturn division, was positively beaming as she accepted the award.   "Sometimes you just have to speak from the heart," she said at the podium. "This car's been through a lot." But a lot of people believe in the brand and have worked hard on its revitalization. "I'm absolutely proud of my people," she said. "It's a great day for General Motors, a great day for Chevrolet, a great day for Saturn."   Lajdziak said later she wasn't surprised by the award, although she did say she was respectful of the competition. She said Saturn continues to "turn heads" with its revitalization. She wouldn't address sales projections, but she said Saturn would let the market tell it how it is doing. (Paul Vigna)     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 10:58 ET (15:58 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Verizon Revolutionizes TV at Home and on Mobile Phones
Story: Verizon President and Chief Operating Officer Strigl: 'We Are the Broadband Company'       LAS VEGAS and BASKING RIDGE, N.J., Jan. 7 /PRNewswire/ -- Ringing in the next great revolution in television, Verizon's new president and chief operating officer Denny Strigl today said the company is leading the way in the next revolution of television. "With the strength of our powerful wireless and fiber networks, we have transformed our business into one of the world's greatest content-delivery systems," he said. To prove the point, Strigl, accompanied by two of Verizon's most senior executives, introduced new products that marry the phone, the Internet and television for consumers in ways not available from any other company.     Speaking on the eve of the International Consumer Electronics Show in Las Vegas, Strigl raised the curtain on two new products that move television to a new level: Verizon's next-generation groundbreaking FiOS TV and V CAST Mobile TV from Verizon Wireless.     Verizon, the premier global telecommunications and content-delivery company, today outlined the new services. Verizon Telecom introduced FiOS digital media new interactive program guide and a platform that offers the company's growing base of FiOS TV customers a myriad of multimedia applications linking television, the Internet, personal computers and phones. Both will be available in the first half of 2007. At the same time, Verizon Wireless raised the curtain on V CAST Mobile TV, unrivalled as the first true mobile TV service in the nation, which is expected to be available in the first quarter of 2007.     Strigl detailed the two-fold strategy behind these products, which crystallizes the changing nature of Verizon's consumer business. "At Verizon, we build great networks and we offer great content. We have built the nation's most comprehensive all-digital broadband fiber network that reaches all the way into individual homes, while we offer the most reliable wireless voice and data network, period," he said.     Verizon FiOS, with unmatched quality and reliability, provides individual homes and businesses in 16 states with up to 50 megabits of Internet speed, and FiOS TV is already available in more than 200 cities in 10 states. Verizon Wireless' broadband network covers more than 200 million people, offering V CAST Video, V CAST Music and BroadbandAccess for high-speed laptop and PDA connectivity.     "Our parallel networks of fiber and wireless create a delivery system for the high-bandwidth content of today, and will meet consumers' needs for years to come," Strigl noted.     Verizon's fiber and wireless broadband networks, and their superior reach, quality and speeds, provide the basis for advancing existing strong partnerships with technology companies such as QUALCOMM Incorporated, whose MediaFLO USA subsidiary supports V CAST Mobile TV. In addition, deep and extensive relationships with leading content providers, appearing on FiOS TV, on Verizon Online and in a variety of mobile platforms to package, format and program TV content, will combine to deliver the best overall TV experience in the industry.     Details about specific service offerings, including availability, pricing and programming, are expected to be available in the coming weeks.        About Verizon     Verizon Communications Inc. (NYSE: VZ), a New York-based Dow 30 company, is a leader in delivering broadband and other wireline and wireless communication innovations to mass market, business, government and wholesale customers. Verizon Wireless operates America's most reliable wireless network, serving nearly 57 million customers nationwide. Verizon's Wireline operations include Verizon Business, which operates one of the most expansive wholly- owned global IP networks, and Verizon Telecom, which is deploying the nation's most advanced fiber-optic network to deliver the benefits of converged communications, information and entertainment services to customers. For more information, visit www.verizon.com.        About Verizon Wireless     Verizon Wireless operates the nation's most reliable wireless voice and data network, serving 57 million customers. The largest US wireless company and largest wireless data provider, based on revenues, Verizon Wireless is headquartered in Basking Ridge, N.J., with 60,000 employees nationwide. Headline: AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK: Is That Bill Ford Or Ted Nugent?
Story: Edited by Paul Vigna     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     (call: 201-938-5172; email: paul.vigna@dowjones.com)   AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK can be found using N/DJMT and I/AUT   12:40 (Dow Jones) Was that a press conference or a rock concert? Ford's (F) flashy press conference featured deafening rock music, a light show and five giant video screens. Executives like Bill Ford Jr. and Mark Fields were driven onto the stage in glistening cars and greeted like guitar heroes. The music was so loud it drowned out the engine on Ford's concept muscle car, the Interceptor. Even Bill Gates was trotted out via satellite to talk about Ford and Microsoft's (MSFT) "Sync" project. 2006 was difficult, Bill Ford said, and 2007 will be pivotal, but the company's laid the foundation for a better Ford. (PJV)   11:05 (Dow Jones) Johnson Control (JCI) is trying to beef up the gadget-connection capability in cars, an issue in the spotlight at this year's North American International Auto Show with the Ford/Microsoft deal. JCI on Sunday unveiled its Mobile Device Gateway, which would allow drivers to use Bluetooth, USB and serial ports to plug in cell phones, MP3 players and other devices and use them as if they were factory-installed. JCI is working with automakers on making it available in 2010 and "maybe even a little earlier," says Scott Wright, vice president of electronic sales and marketing. The system expands on JCI's current Bluetooth system. (TAK)   10:53 (Dow Jones) The media are descending on Detroit. The centennial North American auto show kicks off today, with a full slate of events and hoards of journalists jockeying for position. GM is building the early buzz, with its glitzy runway show last night and its fairly surprising sweep of the North American car and truck awards this morning. The company also has a noon press conference where it will unveil its latest concept car, the Chevy Volt, and talk about getting back into the electric car market - just as soon as it develops a new type of battery. (PJV)     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 12:40 ET (17:40 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Nissan Sees Tough US Sales Next FY Amid Sluggish Demand
Story: By Yoshio Takahashi      Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--Nissan Motor Co. (NSANY) expects tough sales conditions in the next fiscal year in the U.S. despite a plan to launch a slew of new models, the company's chief operating officer said Sunday.   Nissan Chief Operating Officer Toshiyuki Shiga hopes his company's planned launch of a new sport-utility vehicle, the sedan version of the Versa compact and other new models for the next fiscal year that will start in April will support sales for the next fiscal year.   He spoke with reporters on the sidelines of the North American International Auto Show.   The Nissan executive said that overall U.S. sales will likely fall to as low as 16.0 million vehicles in 2007 from 16.5 million in 2006. He told reporters at a round-table meeting that it won't be easy to boost sales amid such a bleak demand picture.   "If overall demand dwindles, incentives will increase" as auto makers will try to spur demand by offering generous sales discounts, he said.   But "we don't want to turn around (the trend of weak demand) just to boost (sales) volume" by increasing sales discounts.   Shiga said Nissan's U.S. sales for this fiscal year ending March 2007 will be nearly flat from the 1.07 million vehicles that it sold in the previous fiscal year ended March 2006.     -By Yoshio Takahashi, Dow Jones Newswires; 813-5255-2929; yoshio.takahashi@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 17:26 ET (22:26 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: INTERVIEW:Daimler's Smart Expects Sales To Rise 07-Pres
Story: By Christoph Rauwald   Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--The president and chief executive of DaimlerChrysler AG's (DCX) Smart minicar division, Ulrich Walker, said Sunday that sales for the Fortwo model are expected to rise in 2007.   "We're expecting the new model to push sales this year above last year's level," Walker told Dow Jones Newswires at the North American International Auto Show.   Walker said the division is "on the safe side" to reach break-even this year.   Following a wide-ranging restructuring program at Smart amid painful losses, DaimlerChrysler aims to reach the break-even point by focusing on the two-seater Fortwo model, nearly a decade after the brand's launch in October 1998. The tiny two-seater is the brand's only remaining model, after the company ceased production of a four-seater and a roadster.   The Smart division saw deliveries fall 22% on the year to 112,100 vehicles in 2006. The Fortwo accounted for around 70% of the unit's sales last year as sales of the Roadtser and Fortwo model were phased out. Walker said the internal targets have been "more than fulfilled" ahead of the upcoming model changeover, without elaborating further.   Smart is set to launch a new version of its tiny two-seater model in April 2007, and plans a U.S. debut for the brand in the first quarter of 2008. For the entry in the U.S. market, DaimlerChrysler signed a General Distributor Agreement, or GDA, with UnitedAuto Group Inc. (UAG) last year. According to previous company statement, DaimlerChrysler estimates the "market potential" to be around 20,000 sales a year.   "I think there a lot of people out there who are looking for low costs of ownership and are concerned about traffic congestion," UnitedAuto Group's CEO Roger Penske told Dow Jones Newswires in Detroit. He declined to give a specific sales target for the Smart brand in the U.S.   "Smart sold around 4,000 cars in Canada in its first year, the U.S. auto market is about 11 times as big as the Canadian, and if we get around 50% of this sales level here, this would be a success," he said.   Penske said he received 1,100 applications from interested dealers for franchises. From these applicants, UAG will choose between 50 and 60 dealers for the brand's launch in the U.S., Penske said, adding that the company will go on a roadshow to Las Vegas, Atlanta, Detroit and New York over the next 30 days.   Penske reiterated that the Smart Fortwo will go on sale for "a price below $15,000".     Company Web site: http://www.daimlerchrysler.com     -By Christoph Rauwald, Dow Jones Newswires; +49 69 29 725 512; christoph.rauwald@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 15:11 ET (20:11 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : LG Mobile Phones and Verizon Wireless Announce the LG VX9400 to support V CAST Mobile TV
Story: Handset Features Innovative Form-Factor Designed Specifically For New Service       LAS VEGAS, Jan. 7 /PRNewswire/ -- Today, LG Electronics MobileComm U.S.A., Inc. (LG Mobile Phones) and Verizon Wireless announced the LG VX9400 will be available in the first quarter to support V CAST Mobile TV, the latest breakthrough in mobile entertainment technology.  The LG VX9400 shows off a slim, stylish swing bar design with a large color LCD for optimal TV viewing and new cutting-edge features, while also offering customers the ability to access V CAST Music and Video, Get It Now(R) and Mobile Web 2.0(SM), plus get Bluetooth(R) capabilities and a 1.3 megapixel camera/camcorder.  All of these multimedia-centric features make the LG VX9400 the must have device for 2007.     The LG VX9400 will be the perfect handset to view Verizon Wireless' all new V CAST Mobile TV service since customers will be able to enjoy the convenience of mobility and entertainment in one device.  Additionally, with the LG VX9400's easy-to-use multitasking capability, users can take calls, messages, and when they hang up, go right back to enjoying their program -- just like if they were to step away from the television set during a program for a minute or two at home.     LG VX9400 users will also have the ability to enjoy the latest in mobile music innovation.  The LG VX9400 is V CAST Music-enabled with a music player, allowing customers to download and listen to the latest hits right on their phones and the external microSD(TM) memory card slot allows them to easily move their music from their computer directly to the phone.  Customers can also take their music with them by transferring files from their phone with a USB connection.  In addition, users can take their music experience to the next level by pairing the LG VX9400 with a Bluetooth stereo headset to gain a totally wireless music experience.     "The LG VX9400 is yet another benchmark in a long line of firsts for LG Mobile Phones," said Juno Cho, president of LG Electronics MobileComm USA., Inc.  "V CAST Mobile TV is truly groundbreaking in mobile phone technology, and we are proud to be among the first manufacturers to support this service that will change the way we use mobile devices forever."     The LG VX9400 complements its robust entertainment capabilities with a full set of mobile features that consumers have come to expect from LG and Verizon Wireless.  The LG VX9400 includes a 1.3 megapixel camera with flash and camcorder that allows users to record up to one hour of consecutive video with an external memory card.  A one-touch speakerphone, Web-based e-mail and Flash User Interface make the LG VX9400 one of the most feature rich handsets available in the U.S. market.     The LG VX9400 offers some of the most advanced mobile phone features available to wireless phone users today, including:          -- V CAST-capable         - V CAST Mobile TV - check out the latest streaming television programs           on your wireless phone         - V CAST Music - download songs over the air or transfer your own music           collection onto a microSD memory card         - V CAST Video and 3D Games - download or stream video clips from the           best names in news, sports, entertainment and more or download the           latest 3D games from top providers      -- Get It Now-capable - download games, Ring Tones, wallpapers and more      -- Mobile Web 2.0-capable - customizable, enhanced wireless access to the         latest in news, sports, weather and more      -- microSD Memory Port to store music, pictures and customer generated         videos (card sold separately)      -- Flash User Interface for Clear Images/Text & Fun Animations      -- Standalone Mode (RF Off)      -- Music Only Mode (RF Off except Bluetooth)      -- 1.3 megapixel camera with flash      -- Self-Portrait capability and mirror for self-portraits      -- Resolution: 1280 x 960, 640 x 480 (default), 320 x 240, 176 x 144, 160         x 120 pixels      -- Video Resolution: 320 x 240, 176 x 144 (default) pixels      -- Up to 4x digital zoom      -- Customizable brightness, white balance, shutter sound, color effects,         photometry, self-timer and night mode      -- Image Editor - zoom, rotate, crop      -- Bluetooth capable (v1.2) - compatible with headset, hands-free, dial-up         networking (SPP), advanced audio distribution, file transfer, object         push for vCard, basic printing, audio/video remote control      -- Bluetooth stereo headset support for listening to music*      -- TXT, Picture and Video Messaging capability - send and receive messages         with text, sounds, photos and videos      -- My Account access - access balance, minutes, usage, and payment info      -- Instant Messaging capability      -- One-touch speakerphone      -- Enhanced speaker-independent voice recognition      -- Voice commands: call, send message, go to, check, lookup, My Account      -- Voice memo recording      -- 13 Unique Ring Tones, plus vibrate and silent modes      -- TTY/TDD support      -- Hearing aid compatible (M4-Rating)      -- Personal organizer with calendar with scheduler, alarm clock, notepad,         plus world clock, calculator, Ez tip calculator tools      -- 500 contacts address book with five numbers, two e-mail addresses and a         picture ID for each entry      -- Speed dial (98 entries plus a voicemail default)      -- English and Spanish language support      -- Simultaneous GPS for Enhanced Location Accuracy      -- Frequency: 1.9 GHz CDMA PCS, 800 MHz CDMA (Digital Dual-Band)      -- Dimensions: 4.04" (H) x 1.93" (W) x 0.73" (D)      -- Weight: 4.06 oz.      -- Soft-Feel coating for comfortable and firm grip      -- Slim and stylish swing bar design with large (2.2") color LCD for          optimal (landscape) TV viewing      -- LCD display: 262K Color TFT, 320 x 240 pixels, 13 lines      -- Standard battery: 950 mAh Li-Polymer      -- Usage time: up to 3 hours and 35 minutes      -- Standby Time: up to 12 days and 12 hours       * The VX9400 supports the following profiles: headset, hands-free, dial-up networking (SPP), file transfer, object push for vCard, basic printing, audio/video remote control and Bluetooth stereo headset support for listening to music. It does not support all Bluetooth object transfer (OBEX) profiles. For vehicle/accessory compatibility, go to www.verizonwireless.com/bluetoothchart.        About Verizon Wireless     Verizon Wireless operates the nation's most reliable wireless voice and data network, serving 57 million customers.  The largest US wireless company and largest wireless data provider, based on revenues, Verizon Wireless is headquartered in Basking Ridge, N.J., with 60,000 employees nationwide.  The company is a joint venture of Verizon Communications (NYSE: VZ) and Vodafone (NYSE and LSE: VOD).  Find more information on the Web at www.verizonwireless.com.  To preview and request broadcast-quality video footage and high-resolution stills of Verizon Wireless operations, log on to the Verizon Wireless Multimedia Library at www.verizonwireless.com/multimedia.        About LG Electronics, Inc.     LG Electronics, Inc. (KSE: 06657.KS) is the global leader and technology innovator in consumer electronics, home appliances and mobile communications, employing more than 72,000 people working in over 120 operations including 80 subsidiaries around the world. Comprised of four business units: Mobile Communications, Digital Appliance, Digital Display and Digital Media with global sales at USD 34.7 billion (consolidated USD 43.4 billion) as of 2005, LG Electronics is the world's leading provider of CDMA handsets, residential air conditioners, plasma panels, optical storage products, DVD players and home theatre system. For more information, please visit www.lge.com.        About LG Electronics Mobile Communications Company     LG Electronics Mobile Communications Company is the world's leading provider of UMTS (WCDMA), CDMA and GSM handsets, which have been designed to improve the value of customer life. With a total range of wired and wireless solutions, the company is rapidly establishing a global presence and growing its international market share in 3G handsets. For more information please visit www.lgusa.com.    SOURCE  Verizon Wireless       /CONTACT: Brenda Boyd Raney of Verizon Wireless, +1-908-559-7518, Brenda.Raney@verizonwireless.com; Melissa Elkins of LG Mobile Phones, +1-858-635-5358, melkins@lge.com; or Keith Carpenter of Ogilvy PR for LG, +1-303-634-2679, Keith.Carpenter@ogilvypr.com      /Web site: http://www.verizonwireless.com      /Web site: http://www.lgusa.com      /Web site: http://www.lge.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 17:00 ET (22:00 GMT)

Headline: New Focus Will Test Ford's Small-Car Moxy
Story: By Terry Kosdrosky     OF DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--If Ford Motor Co. (F) is serious about becoming a bigger player in the small-car segment, a major test comes this year when it launches the 2008 Focus, which has been significantly refreshed.   Besides a new exterior and interior, Ford will offer a two-door coupe version to reach a broader base of buyers. Ford also is updating the look of its larger Five Hundred sedan and giving it a new power train.   The new Focus, which goes on sale in the fall and is being introduced at the North American International Auto Show in Detroit, is Ford's latest weapon in a segment dominated by Japanese players such as Honda Motor Co.'s (HMC) Civic, Toyota Motor Corp.'s (TM) Corolla and Nissan Motor Co.'s (NSANY) Sentra.   Ford is in the midst of cutting tens of thousands of jobs and closing plants amid slumping SUV sales and a steady loss of market share in recent years. The auto maker is not expected to turn a profit in North America until 2009, a year later than originally forecast.   Against this backdrop, Ford is trying to better compete in growing segments, such as crossover utility vehicles - where it has the recently launched Ford Edge - and small cars.   "All signs point to continued growth in small cars," said George Pipas, Ford's chief of sales analysis.   It's also a segment where a lot of younger, first-time buyers enter the market, Pipas said.   "Frankly, we haven't done a great job in this segment," he said.   But Ford thinks the new Focus should change that trend. The 2008 model has a horizontal chrome grille in the manner of the popular Fusion mid-size sedan, a more striking profile and a stronger-looking back end. The interior also has been refined with a more open look and ice blue lighting. Ford also said the new interior cuts down on outside noise.   Sales of the Focus were down 4.2% in 2006, while Corolla sales were up 13.5% and Civic sales were up nearly 3%.   While Ford has only 7% of the small car market, "that is going to change," Pipas said.   The Focus, considering its age, actually has held up well, said Erich Merkle, director of forecasting for IRN Inc. of Grand Rapids, Mich.   He said the new Focus should help stem the sales decline but he doesn't think it will trigger a big sales increase. He noted that Nissan has a new Sentra on the market.   "I think it's going to do more to stabilize their position," Merkle said. "It's a step forward. Unfortunately, there's progress being made in that segment that's greater than a step. My thought is a step forward might not be enough."   Merkle said Ford should have brought its European version of the Focus off the C-1 platform here, but that's not slated to happen until 2011.   "I would rather have seen it this time," Merkle said.   In addition to the Focus, Ford also is trying to give its Five Hundred sedan a push with a redesign and new engine.   Five Hundred sales were down 22% in 2006 and Ford Americas President Mark Fields said the auto maker is trying to "import some of the Fusion magic to the Five Hundred."   The 2008 Five Hundred, which goes on sale in the summer, gets the Fusion-inspired horizontal chrome grille, new tail lamps and a new 3.5-liter Duratec V-6 engine that delivers 60 more horsepower than the previous engine.   Ford also said the interior is quieter, and that the Five Hundred features a new electronic stability control system.     -By Terry Kosdrosky of Dow Jones Newswires; 313-226-1251; terry.kosdrosky@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 00:01 ET (05:01 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: Fraud Office Probes BAE Payments To S Africa
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--The U.K. Serious Fraud Office is investigating payments made by BAE Systems (BA.LN) to a senior South African defense official who had influence over a GBP1.5-billion contract won by the arms company, The Guardian  reported, citing South African sources.   The report said that South Africa's organized crime unit was handling a "mutual legal assistance" request from the U.K. office to investigate the accounts of Fana Hlongwane in relation to the 1999 deal. Hlongwane is a former special adviser to the then South African defense minister, Joe Modise, the report said.. Modise died in 2001.   BAE Systems said Sunday that it "continues to cooperate fully with the SFO investigation." The company added: "As this is a continuing criminal investigation it would be inappropriate for us to comment on the substance of the investigation. Consistent with this, we will not be commenting on any point of substance. Headline: CityDev Sells 95% Of Singapore Apartment Units In 2 Days
Story: SINGAPORE (Dow Jones)--City Developments Ltd. (C09.SG) has sold over 95% of the 341 units in Singapore's first luxury condominium to be launched in 2007, the company said.   In less than two full days, all but a handful of One Shenton's 330 regular units were sold at prices between S$1,500 per square foot and S$2,200 psf, according to a release Saturday from the company.   When the sale commenced Friday, CityDev set prices between S$1,500 and S$2,000 psf, but later widened the range.   The sale compares well with December's launch of the nearby Marina Bay Residences, a 422 unit project that sold out completely in two days at an average price near S$1,850 psf.   Some of the 11 penthouse units on One Shenton's upper floors - which haven't been released for sale yet - will likely command even higher prices.   The average price for mass market condominiums in 2006 was around S$650 psf while the average price for high-end projects was between S$1,600 psf and S$1,700 psf, according to real estate firm Knight Frank Singapore.   CityDev expects construction of One Shenton to be complete in 2011.   About 35% of One Shenton's buyers are foreigners, coming from countries including China, Russia, and Indonesia.     -By John Jannarone, Dow Jones Newswires; 65 6415 4152; john.jannarone@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 03:04 ET (08:04 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : MediaFLO USA Partners With Viacom's MTV Networks to Bring MTV: Music Television, Nickelodeon and COMEDY CENTRAL Programming to Its Mobile Entertainment Service
Story: - Popular Favorites Such as 'The Real World,' 'SpongeBob SquarePants' and 'The Daily Show with Jon Stewart' Added to Revolutionary Mobile TV Service -       SAN DIEGO, Jan. 7 /PRNewswire-FirstCall/ -- MediaFLO(TM) USA Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of QUALCOMM Incorporated (Nasdaq: QCOM), and MTV Networks, a unit of Viacom (NYSE: VIA, VIA.B), today announced a multi-year licensing agreement under which MTV Networks will provide channels branded MTV, Nickelodeon and COMEDY CENTRAL to MediaFLO USA's mobile entertainment service.  MediaFLO USA intends to offer this compelling, full-length content to subscribers 24/7 via their mobile phones in partnership with wireless operators, enabling consumers to enjoy their favorite programs on the go. Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed.     The relationship will bring consumers access to audience favorites including reality, entertainment and children's programming.  MTV content includes the popular reality drama "The Real World;" Nickelodeon offers the pop culture phenomenon "SpongeBob SquarePants;" and COMEDY CENTRAL brings the Peabody and Emmy award-winning "The Daily Show with Jon Stewart."     "Our audiences are the 'mobile generation,' and we've built brands that are vibrant and accessible on every platform to connect with them wherever they are, in the most engaging way possible," said Judy McGrath, chairman and CEO, MTV Networks.  "Our deal with MediaFLO USA enables MTV Networks to provide audiences with a rich new experience and strengthens our position on the forefront of mobile entertainment in the U.S."     "This partnership with MTV Networks is a powerful validation of the mobile multimedia opportunity in the United States, and it underscores the ability of MediaFLO USA to secure the very best content from the world's leading entertainment companies," said Paul Jacobs, chief executive officer, QUALCOMM.     "Our mobile video business continues to grow rapidly as we add more channels, more content and more distribution around the world," said Nicole Browning, president, affiliate sales and marketing, MTV Networks.  "We're thrilled to be partnering with MediaFLO USA and leveraging their innovative service to increase the breadth of our wireless footprint and the depth of our audience connections."     "With must-see content from companies like MTV Networks soon to be available in the first TV-quality mobile media environment, MediaFLO USA is creating a new, additional avenue for audiences to connect with their favorite brands and programming," said Gina Lombardi, president of MediaFLO USA.  "Our market research and consumer trials confirm that wireless subscribers expect exciting, high-quality entertainment and viewing experiences on their handsets, and MTV Networks provides the content that is at the top of their list."     Guided by extensive primary research and consumer trials, MediaFLO USA intends to secure familiar, premium brands from many of the world's leading media companies and leverage its nationwide multicast network to deliver full-length, TV-quality programming to mobile phones.  The agreement with MTV Networks brings an engaging portfolio of youth- and young adult-oriented programming to MediaFLO USA's mobile entertainment service.  MTV is the World's Most Valuable Pure Media Brand for the 7th year in a row, according to the Interbrand/Business Week 2006 survey, "The World's Most Valuable Brands;" Nickelodeon has remained the No. 1 rated basic cable network for more than 11 years, according to Nielsen; and COMEDY CENTRAL is television's only all-comedy network and is the No. 1 basic cable network in primetime among men ages 18-24 for the third straight year, also according to Nielsen.     According to MTVN Global Research, MTV Networks is the world's leading provider of wireless video programming.  In the United States alone, MTVN publishes more than 600 clips and 30 hours of video across all the major wireless carriers.        About MTV Networks and Viacom     MTV Networks, a unit of Viacom (NYSE: VIA, VIA.B), is one of the world's leading creators of programming and content across all media platforms.  MTV Networks, with 135 channels worldwide, owns and operates the following television programming services -- MTV: MUSIC TELEVISION, MTV2, VH1, mtvU, NICKELODEON, NICK at NITE, COMEDY CENTRAL, TV LAND, SPIKE TV, CMT, NOGGIN, THE N, VH1 CLASSIC, LOGO, MTVN INTERNATIONAL and THE DIGITAL SUITE FROM MTV NETWORKS, a package of 13 digital services, all of these networks trademarks of MTV Networks.  MTV Networks connects with its audiences through its robust consumer products businesses and its more than 200 interactive properties worldwide, including online, broadband, wireless and interactive television services and also has licensing agreements, joint ventures and syndication deals whereby all of its programming services can be seen worldwide.     Viacom is a leading global entertainment content company, with prominent and respected brands in focused demographics.  Engaging its audiences through television, motion pictures and digital platforms, Viacom reaches its audiences wherever they consume content.  Viacom's leading brands include the multiplatform properties of MTV Networks, including MTV, VH1, Nickelodeon, Nick at Nite, COMEDY CENTRAL, CMT: Country Music Television, Spike TV, TV Land, Logo and more than 135 networks around the world, as well as digital assets such as Neopets, Xfire and Atom Entertainment; BET Networks; Paramount Pictures; Paramount Home Entertainment; DreamWorks; and Famous Music.  More information about Viacom and its businesses is available at www.viacom.com.        About MediaFLO USA Inc.     MediaFLO USA Inc. aggregates and intends to deliver premium, TV-quality entertainment and information services to mobile phones over its dedicated nationwide wireless network.  Offering an unprecedented combination of full-length programming, short-format clips and realtime information and entertainment feeds, MediaFLO USA will deliver a uniquely compelling mobile viewing experience.  MediaFLO USA intends to partner with world-class content providers, wireless operators and advertisers to make its service available to U.S. consumers in the first quarter of 2007.  Based in San Diego, Calif., MediaFLO USA is a subsidiary of QUALCOMM Incorporated.     Except for the historical information contained herein, this news release contains forward-looking statements that are subject to risks and uncertainties, including the ability of MediaFLO USA to form timely and profitable partnerships with content providers, wireless operators and advertisers, the extent and speed to which FLO technology and the MediaFLO USA network are deployed, the extent and speed of adoption by consumers of MediaFLO USA's service, the speed with which MTV Networks programming is integrated into the MediaFLO USA service package, change in economic conditions of the various markets MediaFLO USA serves, as well as the other risks detailed from time to time in QUALCOMM's SEC reports, including the report on Form 10-K for the year ended September 24, 2006, and most recent Form 10-Q.     QUALCOMM is a registered trademark of QUALCOMM Incorporated.  MediaFLO and FLO are trademarks of QUALCOMM Incorporated.  All other trademarks are the property of their respective owners.          QUALCOMM Contacts:      Julie Reynolds, MediaFLO USA Inc.      Phone:  1-858-845-3516      Email:  julier@mediaflousa.com        Kristin Atkins, Corporate Communications      Phone:  1-858-845-5959      Email:  corpcomm@qualcomm.com        Garrett Ponder, Investor Relations      Phone:  1-858-658-4813      Email:  ir@qualcomm.com        Viacom/MTV Networks Contact:      Mark Jafar, Corporate Communications, MTVN      Phone:  1-212-846-8961      Email:  mark.jafar@mtvstaff.com      SOURCE  MediaFLO USA Inc.       /CONTACT: Julie Reynolds of MediaFLO USA Inc., +1-858-845-3516, julier@mediaflousa.com; or Kristin Atkins, Corporate Communications, +1-858-845-5959, corpcomm@qualcomm.com, or Garrett Ponder, Investor Relations, +1-858-658-4813, ir@qualcomm.com, both of QUALCOMM Incorporated; or Mark Jafar, Corporate Communications of MTV Networks, +1-212-846-8961, mark.jafar@mtvstaff.com, for Viacom/MTV Networks      /Web site: http://www.qualcomm.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 16:00 ET (21:00 GMT)

Headline: GM CEO: Company Aims To Increase US Retail Sales In 2007
Story: By John D. Stoll    Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--General Motors Corp. (GM) Chief Executive Rick Wagoner on Sunday said the company aims to increase retail sales in the U.S. in 2007 after hitting its retail-sales target in the region last year.   Wagoner, speaking to reporters following a speech at the North American International Auto Show, said he expects the overall U.S. vehicle market to be flat in 2007.   GM sold 3 million vehicles to retail customers last year and Wagoner said, "We'd like to tweak that up" in 2007.   Wagoner also said that the company is focused on shoring up its liquidity position, which has been dented by negative cash flow in recent quarters. GM has sold off control in certain assets in order to raise additional cash, but Wagoner insisted GM must get the "operating business into a cash generating position."   The executive cited a $4 billion to $5 billion health-care disadvantage compared to competitors as a major drain on cash. He said the company will address its health care tab and other competitive issues when it negotiates a new contract with the United Auto Workers later this year. Wagoner said the company needs to erase the health-care disadvantage, but did not provide details on a specific strategy.   GM is in the midst of a major restructuring of its North American operations after posting heavy losses in recent years. The company has been losing market share to foreign rivals with leaner cost structures.     -By John D. Stoll, Dow Jones Newswires; (313) 510 5002; john.stoll@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 14:02 ET (19:02 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK: Mulally Sounds Like A Lifer
Story: Edited by Paul Vigna     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     (call: 201-938-5172; email: paul.vigna@dowjones.com)   AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK can be found using N/DJMT and I/AUT   1:08 (Dow Jones) Ford's (F) new leader, Alan Mulally, looked like a lifer in his appearance at the company's press conference. Driven out in a glistening new 500 sedan, Mulally was poised and energetic in discussing Ford's cars and prospects, sounding much like a man who's excited about what he's doing. After the event, North American head Mark Fields - who matched Mulally in the enthusiasm department - said he expects the auto maker's sales will be down slightly, with light vehicle sales of roughly 16.4M, as the US economy slows down. Fields expects GDP of 2%-2.5%, with a moderating job market and weak housing market. (PJV)   12:40 (Dow Jones) Was that a press conference or a rock concert? Ford's (F) flashy press conference featured deafening rock music, a light show and five giant video screens. Executives like Bill Ford Jr. and Mark Fields were driven onto the stage in glistening cars and greeted like guitar heroes. The music was so loud it drowned out the engine on Ford's concept muscle car, the Interceptor. Even Bill Gates was trotted out via satellite to talk about Ford and Microsoft's (MSFT) "Sync" project. 2006 was difficult, Bill Ford said, and 2007 will be pivotal, but the company's laid the foundation for a better Ford. (PJV)   11:05 (Dow Jones) Johnson Control (JCI) is trying to beef up the gadget-connection capability in cars, an issue in the spotlight at this year's North American International Auto Show with the Ford/Microsoft deal. JCI on Sunday unveiled its Mobile Device Gateway, which would allow drivers to use Bluetooth, USB and serial ports to plug in cell phones, MP3 players and other devices and use them as if they were factory-installed. JCI is working with automakers on making it available in 2010 and "maybe even a little earlier," says Scott Wright, vice president of electronic sales and marketing. The system expands on JCI's current Bluetooth system. (TAK)   10:53 (Dow Jones) The media are descending on Detroit. The centennial North American auto show kicks off today, with a full slate of events and hoards of journalists jockeying for position. GM is building the early buzz, with its glitzy runway show last night and its fairly surprising sweep of the North American car and truck awards this morning. The company also has a noon press conference where it will unveil its latest concept car, the Chevy Volt, and talk about getting back into the electric car market - just as soon as it develops a new type of battery. (PJV)     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 13:08 ET (18:08 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UPDATE: Taiwan Government Takes Over Chinese Bank
Story: (Update with comments from Premier Su Tseng-chang and prosecutor)   By Perris Lee Choon Siong   OF DOW JONES NEWSWIRES   TAIPEI (Dow Jones)--Taiwan authorities have banned board members of Chinese Bank (2831.TW) from leaving the island, and have frozen their assets, after the Taiwan government took over management of the lender Friday, government officials said Sunday.   Depositors withdrew more than NT$15 billion from their accounts at the bank Friday, resulting in a liquidity crunch, after two of its sister companies, China Rebar Co. (9801.TW) and Chia Hsin Food & Synthetic Fiber Co. (1207.TW), filed to the Taipei District Court to restructure businesses.  China Rebar and Chia Hsin said years of losses hurt their ability to repay debts.   Taiwan Premier Su Tseng-chang said in a statement the bank's board members and management have been banned from leaving the island, and their assets frozen by authorities, as they are now under investigation.   Su didn't elaborate, but said the government will ensure order in the financial markets Monday.   The government-owned Central Deposit Insurance Corp. took over management and operations of the bank starting Saturday, according to a Financial Supervisory Commission statement late Friday.   And "we have asked the Ministry of the Interior to keep the bank's board members and some management people within the island for further investigation," FSC Acting Spokesman Justin Chan said in a phone interview Sunday.   He said the commission has asked prosecutors to probe whether there was any wrongdoing by the bank's management and board members.   Taipei Prosecutors Office's Spokesman Fred Lin said the prosecutors office is working closely with the FSC to gather information on whether there was any insider-trading or fund embezzlement involved.   Bank officials weren't available for immediate comments Sunday.    According to a Chinese Bank filing to the Taiwan Stock Exchange Friday, it asked the commission to take over its operations because of a liquidity crunch resulting from "abnormal" withdrawals of more than NT$15 billion (US$459.9 million) Friday.  It had a net worth of NT$10.9 billion at the end of October.   In a joint advertisement on major dailies Sunday, Financial Supervisory Commission Chairman Shih Jun-ji, Central Bank of China Governor Perng Fai-nan and Minister of Finance Ho Chih-chin sought to calm depositors, saying the government will fully insure deposits placed at the bank now that it has been taken over.   Chinese Bank, a member of the Rebar Group, operates 35 branches islandwide and has a market share of less than 1% by deposits. It reported a net loss of NT$3.8 billion for the nine months ended Sept. 30, 2006, after losing a net NT$561 million in 2005 and NT$986 million in 2004.   China Rebar and Chia Hsin are also members of the Rebar Group, which has interests in hotel, department stores, and textile businesses.   The Financial Supervisory Commission has also asked the Taiwan Cooperative Bank (5854.TW) and Cathay Financial Holding Co. (2882.TW) to jointly take over the group's Great Chinese Bills Finance Corp. starting Sunday.   Great Chinese suffers from liquidity shortage, the commission said.   -By Perris Lee, Dow Jones Newswires; 8862-2502-2557; perris.lee@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 03:20 ET (08:20 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UK PRESS: HBOS, Hunter Prepare New Crest Nicholson Bid
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--HBOS PLC (HBOS.LN) and Scottish entrepreneur Sir Tom Hunter will this week likely put forward a revised takeover bid of more than GBP680 million for housebuilder Crest Nicholson PLC (CRST.LN), the Sunday Times reported, citing unnamed city sources.   Crest rejected a GBP660 million offer -valued at 585 pence a share -from the consortium, called Castle Bidco Ltd., in November.   The report said that HBOS and Hunter were working on plans for an offer of 600 pence a share in time for a Friday 1700 GMT deadline imposed by Crest Nicholson.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 07:32 ET (12:32 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Design and Technology Rule the Road in GM's North American International Auto Show Introductions
Story: DETROIT, Jan. 7 /PRNewswire/ -- From a sleek, electrically powered concept vehicle that makes trips to the gas station a rarity, to a modern, top-down twist on one of America's favorite muscle cars, design and technology dominate the General Motors exhibit at the 2007 North American International Auto Show, which opens to the public on Jan. 13.     To show off this year's stunning new production and concept vehicles, the all-new, 121,000-square-foot GM exhibit space -- the show's largest -- has been transformed into an art gallery-type setting that complements each of GM's eight vehicle brands and showcases GM's intention to reinvent the automobile with technologies that save fuel, reduce emissions and promote energy independence.     "GM has some of the greatest design and technology talent in the industry, and our Detroit lineup this year proves it," said Mark LaNeve, GM North America vice president, vehicle sales, service and marketing. "If 2006 was about an amazing year of new-product introductions, 2007 is all about momentum."     Four vehicles will make their world debut in Detroit: the Chevrolet Camaro convertible concept, Chevrolet Volt concept, 2008 Chevrolet Malibu and the 2008 Cadillac CTS.     GM's most electrifying advanced technology vehicle introduction, literally, is the Chevrolet Volt concept, a battery-powered, extended-range electric passenger vehicle that uses a gas engine to create additional electricity, making pit stops practically passé. The technology behind the Volt concept, GM's E-flex System, allows electricity to be produced from gasoline, ethanol, bio-diesel or hydrogen, helping to provide a global solution to diversifying transportation energy sources.     On Saturday at GM Style, a glitzy convergence of Hollywood's brightest stars and 17 GM concept and production vehicles, the Chevrolet Camaro convertible concept was introduced, along with the U.S. premiere of four global concepts that will be on display at the auto show.          Here is the complete list of GM vehicle introductions for Detroit:      * All-new 2008 Cadillac CTS (world debut)      * All-new 2008 Chevrolet Malibu (world debut)      * Chevrolet Volt concept (world debut)      * Chevrolet Camaro convertible concept (world debut)      * Chevrolet Equinox Sport      * Chevrolet HHR Premiere Edition      * Pontiac G6 GXP      * Pontiac Torrent GXP      * Pontiac GXP.R race car      * Saab BioPower Hybrid concept (first U.S. introduction)       General Motors Corp. (NYSE: GM), the world's largest automaker, has been the global industry sales leader for 75 years. Founded in 1908, GM today employs about 318,000 people around the world.  With global headquarters in Detroit, GM manufactures its cars and trucks in 33 countries.  In 2005, 9.17 million GM cars and trucks were sold globally under the following brands: Buick, Cadillac, Chevrolet, GMC, GM Daewoo, Holden, HUMMER, Opel, Pontiac, Saab, Saturn and Vauxhall.  GM's OnStar subsidiary is the industry leader in vehicle safety, security and information services.  More information on GM can be found at www.gm.com.    SOURCE  General Motors Corporation       /CONTACT: Laura Toole, Manager, Auto Shows and Events, GM Communications, +1-313-665-3169, or laura.toole@gm.com      /Web site: http://media.gm.com      /Web site: http://www.gm.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 00:01 ET (05:01 GMT)

Headline: UK PRESS: Sainsbury To Cut Prices On 1,000 Items
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--J Sainsbury PLC (SBRY.LN) supermarket group will Thursday announce that it is cutting prices on 1,000 key items, the Sunday Times reported.   The GBP70-million campaign comes after rival Tesco PLC (TSCO.LN) set its own price-cutting move by reducing costs on 600 items by a total of GBP80 million, the report said.   Sainsbury's price cuts will be announced Thursday with the company's trading update, said the report.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk     -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9320     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 07:24 ET (12:24 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Daimler's Smart Unit On Track For Break-Even 07- Pres
Story: - -   *Daimler's Smart Expects Fortwo Sales To Rise 07-Pres *Daimler's Smart Unit On Track For Break-Even 07- Pres *Turnaround Of Daimler's Smart Unit Is Sustainable -Pres =INTERVIEW:Daimler's Smart Expects Sales To Rise 07-Pres  *************************************  ***EMBARGO **** GMT/15:00ET, DAY 07/01***Detroit (unedited)  *************************************     By Christoph Rauwald   Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--The president and chief executive of DaimlerChrysler AG's (DCX) Smart minicar division Ulrich Walker said Sunday sales for the Fortwo model are expected to rise in 2007.   "We're expecting the new model to push sales this year above last year's level," Walker told Dow Jones Newswires at the North American International Auto Show.   Walker said the division is "on the safe side" to reach break-even this year.   Following a wide-ranging restructuring program at Smart amid painful losses, DaimlerChrysler aims to reach break-even at Smart by focusing on the two-seater Fortwo model, nearly a decade after the brand's launch in October 1998. The tiny two-seater Fortwo is the brand's only model after the company ceased production of a four-seater and a roadster model.   The Smart division saw deliveries fall 22% on the year to 112,100 vehicles in full-year 2006. The Fortwo accounted for around 70% of the unit's sales last year as sales of the Roadtser and Fortwo model phased out. Walker said the internal targets have been "more than fulfilled" ahead of the upcoming model changeover, without elaborating further.   Smart is set to launch a new version of its tiny two-seater model in April 2007, and plans a U.S. debut for the brand in the first quarter 2008. For the entry in the U.S. market, DaimlerChrysler signed a General Distributor Agreement, or GDA, with UnitedAuto Group Inc. (UAG) last year. According to previous company statement, DaimlerChrysler estimates the "market potential" to be around 20,000 sales per year.   "I think there a lot of people out there who are looking for low costs of ownership and are concerned about traffic congestion," UnitedAuto Group's CEO Roger Penske told Dow Jones Newswires in Detroit. He declined to give a specific sales target for the Smart brand in the U.S.   "Smart sold around 4,000 cars in Canada in its first year, the U.S. auto market is about eleven times as big as the Canadian, and if we get around 50% of this sales level here, this would be a success," he said.   Penske said he received 1,100 applications from interested dealers for a possible franchises. From these applicants, UAG will choose between 50 and 60 dealers for the brand's launch in the U.S., Penske said, adding that the company will go on a roadshow to Las Vegas, Atlanta, Detroit and New York over the next 30 days.   Penske reiterated that the Smart Fortwo will go on sale for "a price below $15,000".     Company Web site: http://www.daimlerchrysler.com     -By Christoph Rauwald, Dow Jones Newswires; +49 69 29 725 512; christoph.rauwald@dowjones.com  -0-   APDJ-01-07-07 1951GMT<   (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 15:00 ET (20:00 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: SPANISH PRESS: Sabadell In Talks To Buy Bank In Florida

Headline: GERMAN PRESS: Possible BenQ Mobile Buyer Names Conditions
Story: FRANKFURT (Dow Jones)--The possible buyer of BenQ Mobile, a unit of Tawain's BenQ Corp. (2352.TW), has named preconditions for a takeover, German daily Westdeutsche Allgemeine Zeitung reported at the weekend.   The consortium of German and U.S. investors, want regional governments to pay some 800 former BenQ Mobile staff for several months, according to the report.   Those staff are currently in a transfer firm which was set up by Siemens AG (SI) which sold its former unit to BenQ in 2006.   German Daily Der Spiegel will report Monday that the consortium seeks financial compensation of around EUR100 million for taking over the 800 staff and aims to keep the right to use the name 'Siemens', currently held by the BenQ Mobile's parent company BenQ.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.waz.de                         http://www.spiegel.de     -Frankfurt Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-69-29725-500.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 09:14 ET (14:14 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Turnaround Of Daimler's Smart Unit Is Sustainable -Pres
Story: - -   *Daimler's Smart Expects Fortwo Sales To Rise 07-Pres *Daimler's Smart Unit On Track For Break-Even 07- Pres *Turnaround Of Daimler's Smart Unit Is Sustainable -Pres =INTERVIEW:Daimler's Smart Expects Sales To Rise 07-Pres  *************************************  ***EMBARGO **** GMT/15:00ET, DAY 07/01***Detroit (unedited)  *************************************     By Christoph Rauwald   Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--The president and chief executive of DaimlerChrysler AG's (DCX) Smart minicar division Ulrich Walker said Sunday sales for the Fortwo model are expected to rise in 2007.   "We're expecting the new model to push sales this year above last year's level," Walker told Dow Jones Newswires at the North American International Auto Show.   Walker said the division is "on the safe side" to reach break-even this year.   Following a wide-ranging restructuring program at Smart amid painful losses, DaimlerChrysler aims to reach break-even at Smart by focusing on the two-seater Fortwo model, nearly a decade after the brand's launch in October 1998. The tiny two-seater Fortwo is the brand's only model after the company ceased production of a four-seater and a roadster model.   The Smart division saw deliveries fall 22% on the year to 112,100 vehicles in full-year 2006. The Fortwo accounted for around 70% of the unit's sales last year as sales of the Roadtser and Fortwo model phased out. Walker said the internal targets have been "more than fulfilled" ahead of the upcoming model changeover, without elaborating further.   Smart is set to launch a new version of its tiny two-seater model in April 2007, and plans a U.S. debut for the brand in the first quarter 2008. For the entry in the U.S. market, DaimlerChrysler signed a General Distributor Agreement, or GDA, with UnitedAuto Group Inc. (UAG) last year. According to previous company statement, DaimlerChrysler estimates the "market potential" to be around 20,000 sales per year.   "I think there a lot of people out there who are looking for low costs of ownership and are concerned about traffic congestion," UnitedAuto Group's CEO Roger Penske told Dow Jones Newswires in Detroit. He declined to give a specific sales target for the Smart brand in the U.S.   "Smart sold around 4,000 cars in Canada in its first year, the U.S. auto market is about eleven times as big as the Canadian, and if we get around 50% of this sales level here, this would be a success," he said.   Penske said he received 1,100 applications from interested dealers for a possible franchises. From these applicants, UAG will choose between 50 and 60 dealers for the brand's launch in the U.S., Penske said, adding that the company will go on a roadshow to Las Vegas, Atlanta, Detroit and New York over the next 30 days.   Penske reiterated that the Smart Fortwo will go on sale for "a price below $15,000".     Company Web site: http://www.daimlerchrysler.com     -By Christoph Rauwald, Dow Jones Newswires; +49 69 29 725 512; christoph.rauwald@dowjones.com  -0-   APDJ-01-07-07 1951GMT<   (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 15:00 ET (20:00 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Toyota US Exec Mum On Possibly Beating Ford Sales In '07
Story: By Jon Kamp      Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     DETROIT (Dow Jones)--The head of U.S. operations for Toyota Motor Corp. (TM) declined to speculate Sunday on whether the Japanese auto maker could supplant Ford Motor Co. (F) this year in the number two position on the U.S. sales list.   The auto maker is expecting, though, to make strides in what could otherwise be a flat U.S. market, implying it will continue taking share from the competition. Some analysts have projected that this could be the year Toyota moves into the number two slot - something Toyota managed for a handful of months in 2006 - behind General Motors Corp. (GM).   Toyota has backed away from making such projections, and Jim Lentz, Executive Vice President of Toyota Motor Sales USA, stuck to that game plan Sunday at the North American International Auto Show.   "In North America it's tough to say. I don't know where Ford's going to end up," Lentz said, speaking with reporters on the sidelines of a Toyota press conference, where the automaker unveiled the "CrewMax" version of its Tundra pickup truck.   Lentz also backed away from making any statements about potentially surpassing GM on the global stage, and deferred to that auto maker's top position in the U.S. market.   "In the U.S., we're a long way away from General Motors," Lentz said. "Globally, it all depends on what happens. It's not a goal, it's not an objective."   Deference aside, Lentz showed off the four-door Tundra pickup truck that's meant to compete in a U.S. segment where GM and Ford are still dominant. Lentz highlighted the truck's American roots and burly attributes, and said it's expected to be one of two key sales drivers, along with hybrids, for Toyota in 2007.   Lentz reiterated that Toyota's 2007 U.S. sales goal is 2.68 million vehicles. That's up from about 2.54 million vehicles in the U.S. in 2006, according to Autodata Corp. The 2006 total represented a 12.5% climb from 2005.   The 2006 total left Toyota with a 13.3% share of the U.S. market, still significantly less than Ford's 17.4% share. But total Ford sales were off 8% in 2006, indicating the different kind of momentum Toyota and Ford carry into the new year.   Lentz noted that the "vast majority" of Toyota's sales increase will come from the new Tundra this year. The company is also expecting a big contribution from the hybrid version of its popular Camry sedan. Lentz noted that production of the Camry hybrid will about double to around 60,000 vehicles this year.   Lentz said overall industry sales in the U.S. this year may be flat, following sales of about 16.5 million vehicles in 2006, weighed down by the negative influence of plant closures. Ford and GM are in the midst of closing several plants as part of their massive domestic restructuring plans.   But sales in the retail market - which excludes sales to fleet customers like rental agencies - will likely increase this year, Lentz said.     -By Jon Kamp; Dow Jones Newswires; 312-750-4129; jon.kamp@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 14:38 ET (19:38 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK: Where's The Lamborghati Fastarossa?
Story: Edited by Paul Vigna     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES       (call: 201-938-5172; email: paul.vigna@dowjones.com)       AUTO SHOW MARKET TALK can be found using N/DJMT and I/AUT     5:06 (Dow Jones) Without a doubt, some of the most beautiful and powerful cars at the auto show in Detroit are from the House of Sant'Agata Bolognese - Lamborghini. At the decidedly high end of the auto market, Lamborghini has three models on display, the Murcielago LP640 Roadster, the Murcielago LP640 Coupe and the Gallardo Spyder. The Italian luxury auto maker also reported at the show that 2006 was a record year, with 2,087 cars built and sold, up 30.4% from a year ago. The 640 Roadster, first introduced at the Los Angeles auto show in November, will go on sale in the spring. The cost? Roughly $400,000. (PJV)   4:13 (Dow Jones) One of if not the smallest cars here is the Smart car, a DaimlerChrysler (DCX) product that's been popular in Europe and will make its US debut in the 1Q08, being sold through United Auto Group (UAG). The little car - it's being displayed outside Cobo Hall maneuvering through and parking between limos and could almost fit in the bed of a Silverado - is being introduced at the "right time," UAG CEO Roger Penske says. Penske wouldn't make a production estimate, but did say jokingly it would be in the "double digits." Penske was asked how he would reply to potential customers worried about driving such a small car on US roads alongside all those big SUVs. He said the car is small, but it's high-tech and has a plethora of safety features. "It's amazing how resilient it is because of the design." (PJV)   3:52 (Dow Jones) With all the high-tech, space-age know-how on display, it was an usual sight to see a man standing in the lobby of Cobo Hall next to one of the lowest tech vehicles around: a sled. A team of five barking, yelping huskies was attached to the sled, and they ran into the main hall and onto DaimlerChrysler's (DCX) exhibit space, which was covered in a sheet of ice, to kick off DCX's presentation. DCX introduced several new models with its 4matic drive - the general theme being 4matic can handle any terrain - and a few with its Bluetec, clean diesel engines. The dogs were followed by hockey players and ice skaters. "I hope you didn't expect to see me on skates," CEO Dr. Dieter Zetsche said. (PJV)   3:25 (Dow Jones) GM CEO Rick Wagoner says the Chevy Volt electric car "isn't about science projects." The auto maker has set aside hundreds of millions of dollars to get the electric car started, but Wagoner indicates the company will spend significantly more than $500M to make it a reality. Wagoner says the company needs to build more than the 1,000 or so electric cars the company did in its last electric car effort, the abandoned EV1 program, and adds their vision is clearer this time. Instead, GM would ideally like to build "hundreds of thousands, (even) millions a year...this is an opportunity to deliver results." He concedes, however, there are question marks around the technology. "Production time will depend on development of battery technology," he says. (JDS/PI)   2:16 (Dow Jones) GM Vice Chairman Bob Lutz called it an "inconvenient truth" that his company has indeed started development of a new "E-Flex" vehicle, the Chevrolet Volt, which run on electricity as well as biodiesel, ethanol and, yes, gasoline. The Volt has a sporty look, WSJ.com observes, and Lutz noted an electric vehicle can also "look good." The Volt can drive 40 miles before other fuels need to help recharge and Lutz emphasized that 78% of Americans live within 20 miles of work. He said if someone drove to work, ran nearby errands and charged the car every night, the owner would never have to buy gasoline for the lifetime of the vehicle, he said. For now, though, the Volt remains only an intriguing concept. (MS)   (http://blogs.wsj.com/autoshow/)   1:26 (Dow Jones) In the minutes leading up to Chrysler Group's big auto show press conference, there were giant loafs of bread flanking the stage. A kitchen counter was in the middle, as if on a cooking show. Irreverent slices of cartoon bread danced on a giant screen.   What was the theme for this revamped minivan unveiling event - the "best thing since sliced bread" or "something's cooking at Chrysler"? Nope. Instead, it was Chrysler Group's focus on its "bread and butter" vehicles. The DaimlerChrysler AG (DCX) unit rolled out the latest versions of its Dodge Caravan and Chrysler Town & Country minivans, replete with a host of gadgets and options. Not listed: the wood paneling seen on the old Plymouth Voyager minivan, also rolled out as Chrysler touted it's long pioneering position in the vehicle segment.   Chrysler President Tom LaSorda was joined on stage by celebrity chef Bobby Flay, and the two made a couple of quick dishes that represent the Chrysler and Dodge brands - spicy pork loin with mango for Dodge and a smooth chocolate ganache cake for Chrysler.   When LaSorda took a turn icing the cake, Flay told the executive, "I can tell you've spent a lot of time in the hot kitchen," to which LaSorda replied, "The kitchen's been pretty hot lately, I'll tell you," a reference to Chrysler's tough 2006. (JDK, TKS)   1:08 (Dow Jones) Ford's (F) new leader, Alan Mulally, looked like a lifer in his appearance at the company's press conference. Driven out in a glistening new 500 sedan, Mulally was poised and energetic in discussing Ford's cars and prospects, sounding much like a man who's excited about what he's doing. After the event, North American head Mark Fields - who matched Mulally in the enthusiasm department - said he expects the auto maker's sales will be down slightly, with light vehicle sales of roughly 16.4M, as the US economy slows down. Fields expects GDP of 2%-2.5%, with a moderating job market and weak housing market. (PJV)   12:40 (Dow Jones) Was that a press conference or a rock concert? Ford's (F) flashy press conference featured deafening rock music, a light show and five giant video screens. Executives like Bill Ford Jr. and Mark Fields were driven onto the stage in glistening cars and greeted like guitar heroes. The music was so loud it drowned out the engine on Ford's concept muscle car, the Interceptor. Even Bill Gates was trotted out via satellite to talk about Ford and Microsoft's (MSFT) "Sync" project. 2006 was difficult, Bill Ford said, and 2007 will be pivotal, but the company's laid the foundation for a better Ford. (PJV)   11:05 (Dow Jones) Johnson Control (JCI) is trying to beef up the gadget-connection capability in cars, an issue in the spotlight at this year's North American International Auto Show with the Ford/Microsoft deal. JCI on Sunday unveiled its Mobile Device Gateway, which would allow drivers to use Bluetooth, USB and serial ports to plug in cell phones, MP3 players and other devices and use them as if they were factory-installed. JCI is working with automakers on making it available in 2010 and "maybe even a little earlier," says Scott Wright, vice president of electronic sales and marketing. The system expands on JCI's current Bluetooth system. (TAK)   10:53 (Dow Jones) The media are descending on Detroit. The centennial North American auto show kicks off today, with a full slate of events and hoards of journalists jockeying for position. GM is building the early buzz, with its glitzy runway show last night and its fairly surprising sweep of the North American car and truck awards this morning. The company also has a noon press conference where it will unveil its latest concept car, the Chevy Volt, and talk about getting back into the electric car market - just as soon as it develops a new type of battery. (PJV)     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  January 07, 2007 17:06 ET (22:06 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
